   SMALL BUSINESS LOBBIES against proposals for a new civil
rights bill.
   Congressional sponsors of the new bill want to override
several recent Supreme Court decisions that they say weaken
the 1964 Civil Rights Act banning employment discrimination.
But small-business groups argue that the bill would, in
effect, require hiring quotas, which they say would hurt
firms with fewer workers; they focus their lobbying on
President Bush, who has said he won't sign a "quota" bill.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   They also oppose a change that would add punitive damages
for intentional discrimination. An amendment by Missouri GOP
Sen. John Danforth revising some terms "doesn't begin to
solve the problem," says Nancy Fulco, human resources
attorney for the U.S. Chamber of Commerce.
   Compared with the current law, the language of the new
bill would make it harder for an employer to prove that its
hiring process is fair, says John Galles, executive vice
president of National Small Business United. But an aide to
Sen. Danforth says the new wording simply summarizes the
essence of earlier civil rights case law. And as for damages,
Ralph Neas, executive director of the Leadership Conference
on Civil Rights, adds: "We've said from the beginning that
this bill has two purposes: to overturn five Supreme Court
decisions and to add monetary damages for intentional
discrimination."
   The bill's backers deny that the legislation would
effectively mandate quotas and accuse opponents of trying to
delay passage.
