   CLEAN AIR COMPROMISES by the House make small firms
breathe easier.
   Small business won two important amendments in the clean
air bill passed last week by the House. One amendment would
enable a small business to reduce emissions by using
reformulated chemicals or operating at different hours
instead of simply buying costly anti-pollution equipment.
Another would let companies apply for one emissions permit in
their home state, which then would automatically seek the
U.S. Environmental Protection Agency's approval. The original
bill required seeking separate permits from the home state,
all contiguous states and the federal government.
   The separate clean air bill passed earlier by the Senate
says the states should decide permit issues. But "if Congress
doesn't take care of this now, they'll have to come back and
fix it within a year, like kids coming back to do extra work
after school," says Christian Braunlich, director of the
National Association of Manufacturers' small manufacturers'
forum.
   Small furniture manufacturers are relieved that the House
measure also would require states to give small concerns
technical compliance information. The American Furniture
Manufacturers Association says that because of California's
air-quality rules, its industry has lost about 2,000 of the
14,000 jobs it once had in Southern California.
   A House-Senate conference will iron out differences
between the two bills. Small-business lobbyists believe the
favorable House provisions will be retained in the final
clean air package sent to President Bush.
