   IT'S A MYTH that small businesses create most of the
nation's jobs, three economists argue in a new book,
"Employers Large and Small," (Harvard University Press). The
book, by Harvard's James Medoff and James Hamilton and
University of Michigan's Charles Brown, seeks to debunk the
theory, prominently espoused by economist and consultant
David Birch, that most job growth depends on entrepreneurs.
The authors argue that when the high failure rate of small
concerns is considered, they create jobs roughly in
proportion to their share of the work force. Mr. Birch
counters that federal studies support his view that small
firms create a disproportionate share of new jobs.
   ---
   A NEW CANDIDATE emerges for the Small Business
Administration's chief counsel for advocacy, a post vacant
since last fall. Robert Hsueh, an immigration lawyer from
Texas, has been through the rigorous government background
check and is expected to be the nominee. The Bush
administration's last nominee, educator Kyo Jhin, withdrew
from consideration in February.
